You just give me one good reason
why l should. Tell me.

239
00:15:42,366 --> 00:15:45,824
Because the show means promotion.
Promotion means ratings.

240
00:15:45,903 --> 00:15:48,667
And ratings mean money.

241
00:15:51,141 --> 00:15:52,301
Money?

242
00:15:53,243 --> 00:15:55,074
Why can't it be me and Jones?

243
00:15:55,145 --> 00:15:57,705
Because we've sold the public
on you and the family.

244
00:15:57,781 --> 00:15:59,339
Now you've got to deliver.

245
00:15:59,416 --> 00:16:02,180
You promised me this would
never happen. You promised me!

246
00:16:02,252 --> 00:16:05,278
-You and l both know l can't cook.
-Don't say that so loud.

247
00:16:05,356 --> 00:16:09,690
-l can't cook, Alex. l can't cook!
-What are you moaning about?

248
00:16:10,794 --> 00:16:12,193
l saved you.

249
00:16:12,262 --> 00:16:15,959
What were you before l rescued you
from that dead-end magazine?

250
00:16:16,033 --> 00:16:18,228
-Happy, l was happy.
-A no-nothing writer.

251
00:16:18,302 --> 00:16:21,863
-That's what l was. l was happy.
-Oh, poor baby. And now you're famous.

252
00:16:21,939 --> 00:16:23,964
That's right. And in debt.

253
00:16:24,108 --> 00:16:28,340
Everybody needs fairy tales.
People need cooking, home, devotion.

254
00:16:28,412 --> 00:16:31,472
-So Cinderella becomes a pumpkin.
-This pumpkin says no.

255
00:16:31,548 --> 00:16:34,449
Well, if you won't do it for us,
do it for Josie.

256
00:16:34,518 --> 00:16:37,112
Think of the little people on the set.
They need it.

257
00:16:37,187 --> 00:16:40,748
-What about Tanya, the cue card girl?
-Her name is Theresa.

258
00:16:41,091 --> 00:16:45,027
l won't do it. No way!
lt's out of the question.

259
00:16:45,362 --> 00:16:48,160
l know it's a lot to ask, Tyler.
l do know that.

260
00:16:48,232 --> 00:16:49,893
lt'll only be for a couple of days.

261
00:16:49,967 --> 00:16:51,491
-lmpossible.
-Why?

262
00:16:51,568 --> 00:16:53,729
Look, do you think l like doing this?

263
00:16:53,804 --> 00:16:57,205
Do you think l live to hand out menus
for Chocki's Chicken Chuckwagon?

264
00:16:57,274 --> 00:16:59,606
-You look very cute.
-Oh, really?

265
00:16:59,743 --> 00:17:02,871
When was the last time
you had to wear a feather suit to work?

266
00:17:02,946 --> 00:17:06,473
l'm an actor. l have an audition
on the 27th, and l need to prepare.

267
00:17:06,550 --> 00:17:09,610
-And l need to cook for Elizabeth.
-Wait a minute.

268
00:17:09,686 --> 00:17:12,746
l got a great idea.
Why not look at it this way?

269
00:17:12,823 --> 00:17:16,224
l mean, you could prepare
as my son-in-law out in Connecticut.

270
00:17:16,293 --> 00:17:19,956
This might be the opportunity
that you've been thinking of.

271
00:17:20,030 --> 00:17:23,193
Think of all the people
that will be seeing you on this special.

272
00:17:23,267 --> 00:17:25,861
-Directors, agents--
-The operative word is your special.

273
00:17:25,936 --> 00:17:27,369
No one's gonna notice me.

274
00:17:27,438 --> 00:17:30,930
l'll just be an insignificant speck
in the constellation of your stardom.

275
00:17:31,008 --> 00:17:33,909
-Why must you always do this, Tyler?
-Look, l need a break!

276
00:17:33,977 --> 00:17:36,275
-He needs a break.
-l need to be noticed.

277
00:17:36,346 --> 00:17:39,076
And not as Elizabeth Blane's son,
but as an artist.

278
00:17:39,149 --> 00:17:41,743
Why don't you tell her
what you're auditioning for?

279
00:17:41,819 --> 00:17:45,050
-What are you auditioning for?
-For a serial killer on Days of Love.

280
00:17:45,122 --> 00:17:46,384
-lsn't that nice?
-Real art.

281
00:17:46,457 --> 00:17:48,618
Sure, it's a good time to joke about it now.

282
00:17:48,692 --> 00:17:51,627
What about two years from now?
What if this turns into a lead?

283
00:17:51,695 --> 00:17:55,859
Then we'll be talking a totally different
story. l'm not gonna blow this audition.

284
00:17:55,933 --> 00:17:59,300
lf you don't do this, l could be out of a job,
we'd be on the streets.

285
00:17:59,369 --> 00:18:01,894
-So adjust.
-You can adjust, Tyler.

286
00:18:02,239 --> 00:18:03,968
Adjustment is nice.

287
00:18:08,679 --> 00:18:11,375
You never cease to amaze me, Jefferson.

288
00:18:11,715 --> 00:18:13,239
Even burned my pipe.

289
00:18:13,317 --> 00:18:15,808
You? On some cooking show.

290
00:18:16,653 --> 00:18:18,382
l don't believe it.

291
00:18:19,857 --> 00:18:23,293
Elizabeth Blane is not only
America's favorite cook...

292
00:18:23,861 --> 00:18:27,558
she's America's favorite mom.
Got a husband, kid...

293
00:18:27,965 --> 00:18:31,492
grandkid, people. Lots of people, get it?

294
00:18:32,135 --> 00:18:33,727
You hate people.

295
00:18:34,137 --> 00:18:35,536
So why do it?

296
00:18:35,606 --> 00:18:37,506
l got 25,000 reasons:

297
00:18:37,941 --> 00:18:40,876
one for every dollar
the network's paying me.

298
00:18:43,213 --> 00:18:45,875
You're not going Hollywood on me,
are you?

299
00:18:45,949 --> 00:18:48,509
Listen, these people want to think...

300
00:18:48,585 --> 00:18:52,453
l sit around dreaming about
this Blane woman's Christmas goose...

301
00:18:52,756 --> 00:18:54,417
whatever that is.

302
00:18:55,158 --> 00:18:57,353
lf it gets me the money
to put this back up...

303
00:18:57,427 --> 00:18:59,657
l can put up with her stuff
for a couple of days.

304
00:18:59,730 --> 00:19:02,198
Elizabeth Blane
hunts her own Christmas goose.

305
00:19:02,266 --> 00:19:03,733
She's famous for it.

306
00:19:03,800 --> 00:19:05,961
You're such a big fan, you better brush up.

307
00:19:06,036 --> 00:19:07,230
l will.

308
00:19:08,138 --> 00:19:10,971
-When are you leaving?
-Soon as l'm packed.

309
00:19:19,349 --> 00:19:20,714
l'm packed.

310
00:19:58,188 --> 00:20:00,088
God! What are you doing?

311
00:20:00,157 --> 00:20:02,751
l'm getting in the part
of your loving husband.

312
00:20:02,826 --> 00:20:04,919
Who's your role model, Hugh Hefner?
Look at you.

313
00:20:04,995 --> 00:20:06,986
Let me show you the rest of the house.

314
00:20:07,297 --> 00:20:11,097
-This is the entry hall going through this--
-lt's beautiful.

315
00:20:14,204 --> 00:20:17,196
-What was that, dear?
-That was my nephew, Andrew.

316
00:20:17,274 --> 00:20:18,502
Anthony!

317
00:20:18,909 --> 00:20:20,399
My name's Anthony.

318
00:20:20,477 --> 00:20:22,809
Your name is Kevin,
and he's your grandson.

319
00:20:22,879 --> 00:20:24,210
-He doesn't look seven.
-l'm 10.

320
00:20:24,281 --> 00:20:25,475
lt's close enough.

321
00:20:25,549 --> 00:20:27,073
-Where's the TV?
-l don't know.

322
00:20:27,150 --> 00:20:29,482
-What good are you?
-l don't know.

323
00:20:29,553 --> 00:20:30,986
Mrs. B?

324
00:20:31,054 --> 00:20:34,581
Norah, l'm so glad to see you.
l know you....

325
00:20:34,658 --> 00:20:37,718
-Who's this? l don't know this.
-This is my sister's other kid.

326
00:20:37,794 --> 00:20:41,286
Your grandchild, Melissa.
lsn't she adorable?

327
00:20:41,365 --> 00:20:43,162
She's got your eyes and my--

328
00:20:44,034 --> 00:20:45,661
What is going on?

329
00:20:48,138 --> 00:20:50,106
Why is everybody.... What?

330
00:20:52,809 --> 00:20:54,276
l'll get her bottle.

331
00:20:55,545 --> 00:20:56,705
Hello.

332
00:20:58,515 --> 00:21:02,042
l know exactly how you feel, dear.
lt's okay.

333
00:21:05,222 --> 00:21:06,382
Right.

334
00:21:08,091 --> 00:21:11,288
-l don't think she's very happy here.
-Oh, no.

335
00:21:12,329 --> 00:21:14,354
-What is it?
-Drool.

336
00:21:14,531 --> 00:21:15,657
-Drool?
-Here.

337
00:21:15,732 --> 00:21:19,224
What is it doing? Wait a.... Norah. Hello!

338
00:21:25,008 --> 00:21:27,909
Kevin, come and meet
your mother and father.

339
00:21:28,679 --> 00:21:30,840
-Anthony!
-What?

340
00:21:33,316 --> 00:21:36,752
Now listen to me. Your name is Kevin.
When l say Kevin, you come, okay?

341
00:21:36,820 --> 00:21:39,220
-You can call me--
-Grandmother? Granny? Gramps?

342
00:21:39,289 --> 00:21:41,314
You call me that, l'll put you in my soup.

343
00:21:43,960 --> 00:21:47,225
Tyler, l'm so glad to see you.
Kevin, this is your father.

344
00:21:47,297 --> 00:21:50,323
Ever wondered what it would feel like
to sew your eyes closed?

345
00:21:50,400 --> 00:21:51,799
-Charming.
-Cool.

346
00:21:51,868 --> 00:21:54,564
He's in character. He refuses to give up
the soap audition.

347
00:21:54,638 --> 00:21:56,469
What about the character
of my son-in-law?

348
00:21:56,540 --> 00:21:58,405
-l'm here, aren't l?
-Thank you very much.

349
00:21:58,475 --> 00:21:59,874
-We fought all the way.
-How come?

350
00:21:59,943 --> 00:22:02,935
l'll tell you later.
Hon, where are you going?

351
00:22:03,046 --> 00:22:05,571
-l'll be back.
-l love that guy.

352
00:22:05,649 --> 00:22:08,277
This is your mother.
Kevin, l'm talking to you!

353
00:22:08,351 --> 00:22:11,047
-ls he all right?
-He's just a little strange, that's all.

354
00:22:11,121 --> 00:22:13,316
-The kitchen's there.
-Don't touch that!

355
00:22:13,390 --> 00:22:15,950
-This is your daughter.
-Don't touch that.

356
00:22:16,026 --> 00:22:17,687
Oh, she is so cute.

357
00:22:20,764 --> 00:22:22,823
-What's the matter?
-Put it down!

358
00:22:23,900 --> 00:22:25,959
No! What are you....

359
00:22:30,040 --> 00:22:31,803
What happened? Not....

360
00:22:32,375 --> 00:22:34,809
-l told you to be careful, didn't l?
-Don't yell!

361
00:22:34,878 --> 00:22:38,609
Do you have any idea how much money
l had to put up as a security deposit?

362
00:22:38,682 --> 00:22:39,774
Hello?

363
00:22:39,850 --> 00:22:41,750
-You idiot!
-l hate you!

364
00:22:44,221 --> 00:22:47,122
Will somebody stop the ringing, please?

365
00:22:47,891 --> 00:22:50,792
What? Who's ringing? Hello?

366
00:22:50,861 --> 00:22:53,352
-Everybody out!
-lt's the fax phone.

367
00:22:54,598 --> 00:22:56,793
Norah, l want to be alone now.

368
00:23:33,603 --> 00:23:34,968
Mrs. Blane?

369
00:23:38,108 --> 00:23:40,599
-Are you okay?
-l'm fine.

370
00:23:41,745 --> 00:23:43,144
Who are you?

371
00:23:45,248 --> 00:23:48,274
-You're Jefferson Jones.
-Afraid so, ma'am.

372
00:23:48,418 --> 00:23:50,386
-What are you doing here?
-Excuse me?

373
00:23:50,453 --> 00:23:52,114
What are you doing here today?

374
00:23:52,189 --> 00:23:55,090
You're not supposed to be here
until the 25th.

375
00:23:55,158 --> 00:23:57,126
-Not according to this fax.
-What fax?

376
00:23:57,194 --> 00:23:58,491
This one.

377
00:24:01,064 --> 00:24:05,364
''Please come early and get to know
my family. Signed, Elizabeth Blane.''

378
00:24:06,236 --> 00:24:08,761
-Stop this!
-You won't listen to my needs, forget it.

379
00:24:08,839 --> 00:24:10,170
What about what l want?

380
00:24:10,240 --> 00:24:11,832
-You're so destructive!
-Not my fault!

381
00:24:11,908 --> 00:24:13,637
You're breaking everything.

382
00:24:13,710 --> 00:24:15,678
Where is the diaper bag?

383
00:24:25,856 --> 00:24:28,086
Mr. Jones, l'd like to introduce my family.

384
00:24:28,158 --> 00:24:30,649
Family, this is Jefferson Jones.

385
00:24:30,760 --> 00:24:34,594
-Jonesy. l see you got my fax.
-Your fax?

386
00:24:35,198 --> 00:24:37,860
l cut a deal with People magazine.

387
00:24:37,934 --> 00:24:40,459
They're gonna write a story
on how America's hostess...

388
00:24:40,537 --> 00:24:43,028
spends three days with America's hero.

389
00:24:43,106 --> 00:24:44,903
lsn't that nice?

390
00:24:45,942 --> 00:24:48,206
Maybe you could just show me
where my room is.

391
00:24:48,278 --> 00:24:50,542
Nonsense. l want you to meet the family.

392
00:24:50,614 --> 00:24:54,345
By the way, l'm Mr. Elizabeth Blane,
but you can call me....

393
00:24:54,417 --> 00:24:57,352
-John Blane.
-John. l'm mighty proud of it.

394
00:24:57,420 --> 00:24:59,752
Mr. Jones, let me introduce you
to my family.

395
00:24:59,823 --> 00:25:03,691
l'd like you to meet my daughter, Mary,
and her husband, Evan.

396
00:25:04,561 --> 00:25:07,496
l love the smell of human hair
when it burns.

397
00:25:09,666 --> 00:25:12,362
l've been traveling all night.
Maybe l could go wash up?

398
00:25:12,435 --> 00:25:14,528
Can l have my allowance now?

399
00:25:14,604 --> 00:25:18,267
-l beg your pardon, dear?
-My special $10 allowance, Granny.

400
00:25:18,475 --> 00:25:21,103
Ask your grandfather. Get it from him.

401
00:25:22,412 --> 00:25:25,939
And this little pudge-face
is my granddaughter, Melissa.

402
00:25:26,583 --> 00:25:28,107
She's so cute.

403
00:25:29,085 --> 00:25:30,848
She's got your eyes.

404
00:25:32,656 --> 00:25:36,524
lt's hard to believe, looking at you,
that you got two grandchildren.

405
00:25:36,593 --> 00:25:39,585
l find it really hard to believe it
myself sometimes.

406
00:25:39,663 --> 00:25:41,221
We are vampires.

407
00:25:41,564 --> 00:25:44,590
We suck the blood of innocents
and stay forever young.

408
00:25:44,668 --> 00:25:47,603
Sweet. Mary, why don't you and Evan
take the children upstairs?

409
00:25:47,671 --> 00:25:48,865
l'll hold it for you.

410
00:25:48,939 --> 00:25:50,964
Will you show Mr. Jones
to his room, please?

411
00:25:51,041 --> 00:25:52,508
-Sure.
-That'd be good.

412
00:25:52,575 --> 00:25:56,170
-Sure. Which one?
-Norah hasn't been with us for very long.

413
00:25:56,246 --> 00:25:58,180
lt's the first one on the left. Thank you.

414
00:25:58,248 --> 00:26:00,375
When should l start dinner?

415
00:26:06,089 --> 00:26:09,058
-Are you the cook?
-Of course l'm the cook.

416
00:26:09,359 --> 00:26:11,156
But that's my occupation.

417
00:26:11,227 --> 00:26:12,922
So since l'm on vacation...

418
00:26:12,996 --> 00:26:15,464
Mary's gonna take over in the kitchen
until Christmas.

419
00:26:15,532 --> 00:26:18,092
Thanks, Mary. Any time you want now.

420
00:26:23,373 --> 00:26:25,273
You have an interesting family.

421
00:26:25,342 --> 00:26:27,833
Yes, aren't they? Very interesting.

422
00:27:08,551 --> 00:27:10,542
That's very manly of you.

423
00:27:11,254 --> 00:27:13,654
-You were running low.
-Thank you.

424
00:27:17,894 --> 00:27:20,260
l suppose you just love being outside.

425
00:27:20,330 --> 00:27:23,857
l mean, coming from
that mountainly place you come from.

426
00:27:23,933 --> 00:27:25,594
Colorado.

427
00:27:29,039 --> 00:27:30,165
Smell that?

428
00:27:30,240 --> 00:27:34,006
Oh, yes, that's my Chanel No. 5.

429
00:27:45,055 --> 00:27:46,420
lt's cedar.

430
00:27:49,259 --> 00:27:51,784
Of course. Cedar.

431
00:27:53,396 --> 00:27:56,126
l bet you can't buy that at Bloomingdale's.

432
00:27:56,199 --> 00:27:57,666
You're right.

433
00:28:05,475 --> 00:28:08,308
How long did you live alone up in that...

434
00:28:08,845 --> 00:28:10,244
cabin place?

435
00:28:10,413 --> 00:28:12,381
-Eleven years.
-Eleven years?

436
00:28:13,716 --> 00:28:15,843
Alone, alone? l mean, no....

437
00:28:16,319 --> 00:28:17,946
-Women?
-Pets.

438
00:28:18,221 --> 00:28:19,449
Neither.

439
00:28:19,923 --> 00:28:22,016
That's a long time.

440
00:28:23,026 --> 00:28:25,517
-l thought about it a lot.
-Women?

441
00:28:25,595 --> 00:28:26,687
Pets.

442
00:28:32,669 --> 00:28:34,000
Excuse me.

443
00:28:41,311 --> 00:28:42,608
Hi, Mary.

444
00:28:44,147 --> 00:28:45,944
l can't do this.

445
00:28:46,116 --> 00:28:49,916
Why? What's the matter?
Hi, sweetie. What's the matter, Mary?

446
00:28:51,020 --> 00:28:55,719
-Mary's under a lot of stress.
-Maybe we should finish up for her.

447
00:28:55,792 --> 00:28:57,851
-Finish up what?
-Her bath.

448
00:28:58,561 --> 00:29:00,756
You ought to be an expert at this.

449
00:29:00,897 --> 00:29:05,459
No big deal. There's water, there's soap,
there's a rubber duck. lt's pretty routine.

450
00:29:07,070 --> 00:29:10,096
You know what?
l just had the most wonderful idea.

451
00:29:10,173 --> 00:29:12,641
-How would you like to bathe her?
-Me?

452
00:29:12,709 --> 00:29:15,678
Sure, l think it would be fun for you. Here.

453
00:29:15,745 --> 00:29:18,009
Let go of my hair, sweetheart.

454
00:29:19,782 --> 00:29:21,579
You want to get in the bath?

455
00:29:21,651 --> 00:29:24,051
You two just have fun.
l'll see you in a while.

456
00:29:24,120 --> 00:29:27,214
Where are you going?
You're gonna supervise for me?

457
00:29:28,191 --> 00:29:30,853
-Hi, sweetie.
-ls it too hot?

458
00:29:31,694 --> 00:29:32,854
lt is too hot.

459
00:29:32,929 --> 00:29:35,193
-Hi, honey.
-l don't blame you.

460
00:29:36,299 --> 00:29:38,927
-Don't get water in her eyes.
-No, l'm not. l'm okay.

461
00:29:39,002 --> 00:29:41,402
-She got any soap?
-Of course, soap.

462
00:29:41,471 --> 00:29:44,269
Want some soap?
Here's some soap, sweetie.

463
00:29:44,574 --> 00:29:47,236
-ls it just a little hot?
-Here's a duck.

464
00:29:48,978 --> 00:29:51,674
What about her hair? Should we wash it?

465
00:29:51,881 --> 00:29:54,372
Well, l'll rinse and you put shampoo.

466
00:29:54,450 --> 00:29:56,111
All right. Okay.

467
00:29:56,186 --> 00:29:58,780
-That's too much.
-What do you mean, it's too much?

468
00:29:58,855 --> 00:30:02,382
l'm telling you. Watch her eyes, l told you.

469
00:30:02,792 --> 00:30:04,987
Wait a minute. My fault.

470
00:30:05,061 --> 00:30:07,757
Sorry, you're right. You're the expert.

471
00:30:08,164 --> 00:30:10,291
Oh, you sweet thing. Sorry.

472
00:30:14,337 --> 00:30:16,464
l don't know if we got all the soap out.

473
00:30:16,539 --> 00:30:18,530
-We did.
-She likes that.

474
00:30:18,608 --> 00:30:20,667
You're awfully good with that
for a bachelor.

475
00:30:20,743 --> 00:30:24,110
You sure you don't have
a whole slew of kids hidden somewhere?

476
00:30:24,180 --> 00:30:26,978
l nursed a couple of bear cubs
till their mother came back.

477
00:30:27,050 --> 00:30:29,917
-This is better than bear cubs.
-Ain't she a beauty?

478
00:30:32,822 --> 00:30:35,950
Josie, there you are.
Don't you ever do that to me again.

479
00:30:36,025 --> 00:30:38,823
You hand me this small, little,
slippery, wet baby.

480
00:30:38,895 --> 00:30:42,058
l don't know how to handle a baby.
l've never....

481
00:30:42,966 --> 00:30:44,934
What's the matter, babe?

482
00:30:48,304 --> 00:30:50,738
-Do you want to talk about it?
-No.

483
00:30:51,774 --> 00:30:52,866
Okay.

484
00:30:56,446 --> 00:30:58,141
Tyler's leaving me.

485
00:30:59,515 --> 00:31:00,982
Tyler's what?

486
00:31:01,818 --> 00:31:04,480
l want to have a baby, Liz. He doesn't.

487
00:31:04,554 --> 00:31:07,853
Josie, the two of you can work it out,
can't you?

488
00:31:07,924 --> 00:31:11,155
You've seen the way Tyler behaves.
Like Charles Manson.

489
00:31:11,227 --> 00:31:13,525
Do you know what it's like living like that?

490
00:31:13,596 --> 00:31:15,791
When he was up for Felix
in The Odd Couple ...

491
00:31:15,865 --> 00:31:19,062
we had our biggest fight
over a coffee ring on the table.

492
00:31:19,135 --> 00:31:21,433
When he was up for
the stage manager in Our Town...

493
00:31:21,504 --> 00:31:25,235
we had to experience small-town life
by moving in with his parents...

494
00:31:25,308 --> 00:31:26,900
in Dayton, Ohio!

495
00:31:26,976 --> 00:31:30,207
With every new part,
comes a completely different personality.

496
00:31:30,280 --> 00:31:32,680
He's so obsessed with his career.

497
00:31:36,319 --> 00:31:39,311
How are we ever going to have
a life together?

498
00:31:39,922 --> 00:31:41,856
Why don't you just be honest?

499
00:31:41,924 --> 00:31:43,915
lt won't change anything.

500
00:31:44,227 --> 00:31:45,956
You know something?

501
00:31:49,098 --> 00:31:50,395
lt might.

502
00:31:52,969 --> 00:31:54,459
lt just might.

503
00:32:01,377 --> 00:32:03,743
Hey, Jonesy baby, wait a minute.

504
00:32:03,913 --> 00:32:06,177
Mind if l come along with you?

505
00:32:09,652 --> 00:32:12,382
You don't mind me tagging along, do you?

506
00:32:12,522 --> 00:32:14,615
-Come on.
-Nice and nippy. Thanks.

507
00:32:14,724 --> 00:32:16,954
l did want to have a little talk with you...

508
00:32:17,026 --> 00:32:20,052
since l'm the producer
and l'm giving you $25,000 for the show...

509
00:32:20,129 --> 00:32:21,653
l thought l'd tell you what's what.

510
00:32:21,731 --> 00:32:25,098
You're gonna see a part of showbiz
that very few people see.

511
00:32:25,168 --> 00:32:27,728
-You know, show business magic.
-Right.

512
00:32:27,804 --> 00:32:30,830
So l just wanted to bring you up to date
with everything.

513
00:32:30,907 --> 00:32:33,774
There may be a time,
there's just the possibility...

514
00:32:33,843 --> 00:32:36,744
l'm not sure that it's gonna happen,
but it's a possibility...

515
00:32:36,813 --> 00:32:40,305
that somewhere along the line....
lt's really chilly.

516
00:32:40,383 --> 00:32:45,320
...that somewhere along the line
you're not gonna see Elizabeth cook.

517
00:32:47,757 --> 00:32:49,622
You got any questions?

518
00:32:50,059 --> 00:32:51,959
How long have you two been married?

519
00:32:52,061 --> 00:32:54,655
Well, time is relative,
and relative is relative.

520
00:32:54,731 --> 00:32:58,132
But it's been worth every minute of it.
You know what l mean by ''worth.''

521
00:32:58,201 --> 00:32:59,691
She's like a cabernet of love.

522
00:32:59,769 --> 00:33:03,364
She gets richer, fuller,
more intoxicating with age, you know.

523
00:33:03,439 --> 00:33:05,907
You know what l think it is?
l think it's chemical.

524
00:33:05,975 --> 00:33:07,408
Every time l get a whiff of her...

525
00:33:07,477 --> 00:33:09,570
l wanna take her in my arms
and give her a kiss.

526
00:33:09,645 --> 00:33:12,739
You know what drives her crazy?
When l suck her toes.

527
00:33:12,815 --> 00:33:15,010
She goes crazy, like a horse.

528
00:33:17,653 --> 00:33:20,520
But look who l'm talking to.
A good-looking guy like you.

529
00:33:20,590 --> 00:33:23,354
You're out there getting all that action.

530
00:33:23,426 --> 00:33:26,589
-Nobody ever neighed for me.
-That takes a little special finesse.

531
00:33:26,662 --> 00:33:29,187
l could teach you how to do it, if you want.

532
00:33:29,265 --> 00:33:33,133
Can l ask you a question, please?
lt's 40 degrees below zero out here.

533
00:33:33,202 --> 00:33:36,603
-What are we doing here?
-l was taking a walk.

534
00:33:38,708 --> 00:33:40,232
Enjoy yourself.

535
00:33:43,613 --> 00:33:47,572
Without the cover, you got no story.
l told you that. You're late.

536
00:33:48,184 --> 00:33:50,084
You snooze, you lose.

537
00:33:57,894 --> 00:34:01,853
Tell me something: Do you dream in color?
Or in black and white?

538
00:34:05,635 --> 00:34:08,331
Would you please pass me that end piece?

539
00:34:08,504 --> 00:34:10,495
Can l have some potatoes?

540
00:34:12,842 --> 00:34:16,642
-ls your food all right?
-Yeah, l just fill up quick these days.

541
00:34:16,712 --> 00:34:18,646
Of course, after what you've been through.

542
00:34:18,714 --> 00:34:22,514
Hey, mister, if they didn't find you,
would you have eaten that kid?

543
00:34:24,287 --> 00:34:26,346
-l don't think so.
-Pass the potatoes.

544
00:34:26,422 --> 00:34:28,356
Would you have eaten your own foot?

545
00:34:28,424 --> 00:34:29,652
-Kevin!
-Maybe.

546
00:34:29,725 --> 00:34:32,751
-Would you like some peas?
-How do you like this chow?

547
00:34:33,262 --> 00:34:37,096
l bet you didn't run across
any Chateaubriand in the forest, did you?

548
00:34:37,166 --> 00:34:38,997
No, this is real good.

549
00:34:39,068 --> 00:34:41,093
l guess l'm just more...

550
00:34:41,170 --> 00:34:44,936
a 4:00 a.m. black-coffee-bacon-
and-flapjacks kind of person.

551
00:34:45,007 --> 00:34:47,339
Flapjack? What a coincidence.

552
00:34:47,410 --> 00:34:50,379
Elizabeth wrote a whole book
about flapjacks.

553
00:34:50,713 --> 00:34:53,614
-You want flapjacks?
-Mary will cook them in the morning.

554
00:34:53,683 --> 00:34:55,981
-The potatoes?
-l love flapjacks.

555
00:34:56,052 --> 00:34:58,384
-Pass the potatoes!
-Here!

556
00:35:02,625 --> 00:35:03,853
Shut up!

557
00:35:03,960 --> 00:35:06,520
Do you have to talk to him that way?
He's only a kid.

558
00:35:06,596 --> 00:35:09,463
-You're the big expert on kids, right?
-At least l want them !

559
00:35:09,532 --> 00:35:10,658
Fine.

560
00:35:17,073 --> 00:35:18,563
Dessert, anyone?

561
00:35:20,910 --> 00:35:23,401
l noticed you don't have a Christmas tree.

562
00:35:24,180 --> 00:35:27,172
-There's a good reason for that.
-Very good reason for that.

563
00:35:27,250 --> 00:35:29,650
We have to wait until Christmas.

564
00:35:31,087 --> 00:35:33,351
-We wait until Christmas.
-Why?

565
00:35:33,456 --> 00:35:34,514
Why?

566
00:35:35,558 --> 00:35:38,994
-For the show.
-Of course, our show. Absolutely.

567
00:35:39,428 --> 00:35:42,420
See, the set decorator comes in
and he does the whole house.

568
00:35:42,498 --> 00:35:44,261
Oh, the whole house.

569
00:35:44,333 --> 00:35:46,198
-Every nook and cranny.
-Yes.

570
00:35:46,802 --> 00:35:49,168
-Normally--
-We have a huge Christmas tree.

571
00:35:49,238 --> 00:35:51,763
-Really big.
-Yes, a veritable redwood, you know?

572
00:35:51,841 --> 00:35:54,571
-But this year, we have prime-time.
-Yes.

573
00:35:58,047 --> 00:36:00,277
Mr. Jones, you're such a fascinating man.

574
00:36:00,349 --> 00:36:02,977
l was just wondering,
have you always been a park ranger?

575
00:36:03,052 --> 00:36:07,546
Actually, before l moved to Colorado,
l lived in Chicago. l grew up there.

576
00:36:08,958 --> 00:36:11,950
Taught Comparative Literature
at the University for 10 years.

577
00:36:12,028 --> 00:36:13,461
Really? Wow!

578
00:36:13,996 --> 00:36:15,554
Then l quit and moved west.

579
00:36:15,631 --> 00:36:18,099
Why? l mean,
why would you give up teaching?

580
00:36:18,167 --> 00:36:20,829
l got offered tenure
and Head of the Department...

581
00:36:20,903 --> 00:36:22,962
and it's what l thought l wanted.

582
00:36:23,039 --> 00:36:25,530
But it meant being caged in...

583
00:36:25,608 --> 00:36:28,270
by concrete and crowds
for the rest of my life.

584
00:36:28,344 --> 00:36:32,678
One day l went to work, and it was
like going into a long, dark tunnel.

585
00:36:33,082 --> 00:36:36,347
l knew l was never going to see
the other end. l couldn't do it.

586
00:36:36,419 --> 00:36:40,082
People were telling me what to do.
l had to be outdoors.

587
00:36:40,156 --> 00:36:43,387
You know what l'm talking about,
living out here.

588
00:36:44,360 --> 00:36:45,725
Excuse me.

589
00:36:46,228 --> 00:36:49,527
l admire you for giving up the city,
you know...

590
00:36:49,599 --> 00:36:52,033
to raise a family in the country.

591
00:36:56,272 --> 00:36:59,070
-You figured it out before l did.
-We try.

592
00:36:59,875 --> 00:37:02,275
Well, it's been a long day.

593
00:37:02,645 --> 00:37:04,670
l think l'm gonna turn in.

594
00:37:04,880 --> 00:37:06,507
-Elizabeth?
-What?

595
00:37:06,749 --> 00:37:09,149
-Time to go to bed.
-Together?

596
00:37:09,719 --> 00:37:12,187
l mean, it's only 9:30, dear.

597
00:37:12,254 --> 00:37:14,245
But you know what they say
in the country.

598
00:37:14,323 --> 00:37:17,053
-What do they say?
-Early to bed, early to rise.

599
00:37:17,126 --> 00:37:21,085
That's if you've got cows and things.
This is Connecticut, and we've got guests.

600
00:37:21,163 --> 00:37:24,564
-You go to bed.
-But you know l can't sleep without you.

601
00:37:24,634 --> 00:37:26,158
We're like two spoons.

602
00:37:26,235 --> 00:37:29,602
For God's sakes, John,
what are you talking about?

603
00:37:29,672 --> 00:37:31,435
-Well, l mean--
-We have company.

604
00:37:31,507 --> 00:37:34,476
Please, Jonesy's a grown man.
You and l are adults--

605
00:37:34,543 --> 00:37:36,340
-You're a grown man, too.
-Yes, but still.

606
00:37:36,412 --> 00:37:38,312
-Go to bed alone.
-l don't wanna go alone.

607
00:37:38,381 --> 00:37:40,849
-Dear, l want you to.
-You all go on.

608
00:37:40,916 --> 00:37:42,941
-No! We don't have to go.
-Mom !

609
00:37:43,019 --> 00:37:44,111
Yes?

610
00:37:44,186 --> 00:37:46,518
-Can you come up here?
-Yes, of course l will.

611
00:37:46,589 --> 00:37:49,319
No, she can't.
Mom and Dad are going to bed.

612
00:37:49,392 --> 00:37:50,586
What is it, darling?

613
00:37:50,660 --> 00:37:53,754
Kevin wants Grandma
to read him a bedtime story.

614
00:37:54,764 --> 00:37:57,733
Kevin wants Grandma
to read him a bedtime story.

615
00:37:57,800 --> 00:38:00,792
l couldn't disappoint Kevin.
Excuse me please, Mr. Jones.

616
00:38:06,676 --> 00:38:08,439
She's such a mother.

617
00:38:11,080 --> 00:38:13,640
Kevin, you want to make $20 cash
right now?

618
00:38:13,716 --> 00:38:17,015
Get in bed, pretend like
l'm reading to you. Hustle.

619
00:38:24,794 --> 00:38:28,252
''lt was his destiny to slay the dragon...

620
00:38:28,798 --> 00:38:30,663
''and save the kingdom.

621
00:38:31,400 --> 00:38:35,336
''The great big kingdom was there.''
Absolutely there.

622
00:38:40,843 --> 00:38:43,209
Hey, where's my $20?

623
00:38:44,980 --> 00:38:47,847
For $50, l can fake a nightmare
and sleep in your bed.

624
00:38:47,917 --> 00:38:51,318
Thanks, Kevo. l'll keep that in mind.
l'll remember that.

625
00:38:57,460 --> 00:38:59,655
Thought you were going to bed?

626
00:39:00,996 --> 00:39:04,864
l was. Just, you know, doing my exercises.

627
00:39:04,934 --> 00:39:07,767
Very important to stay in shape,
you know.

628
00:39:09,305 --> 00:39:11,273
-Good night!
-Good night.

629
00:39:17,513 --> 00:39:19,378
Forgot the toothpaste.

630
00:39:43,105 --> 00:39:46,802
Norah, you scared me half to death.

631
00:39:46,876 --> 00:39:49,868
-What are you doing down here?
-l was fixing myself a snack.

632
00:39:49,945 --> 00:39:51,845
l heard a woman scream.

633
00:39:52,348 --> 00:39:54,680
We didn't hear anything, did we?

634
00:39:55,451 --> 00:39:58,181
-l thought you were going to bed.
-So did l.

635
00:39:58,254 --> 00:39:59,551
So did l.

636
00:40:00,723 --> 00:40:02,088
Good night.

637
00:40:03,192 --> 00:40:04,819
-Mrs. Blane?
-Yes?

638
00:40:05,094 --> 00:40:08,291
-Are you going for the goose tomorrow?
-The goose?

639
00:40:08,364 --> 00:40:09,991
The Christmas goose.

640
00:40:10,065 --> 00:40:12,397
The one we hunt
every Christmas Eve morning...

641
00:40:12,468 --> 00:40:14,595
after having slept all night together.

642
00:40:14,670 --> 00:40:16,399
That goose. l knew what goose.

643
00:40:16,472 --> 00:40:19,134
l thought this year, with the show,
we wouldn't do that.

644
00:40:19,208 --> 00:40:21,540
l'd love to come along with you.

645
00:40:21,977 --> 00:40:24,878
-l saw a whole flock of geese this morning.
-You can't.

646
00:40:24,947 --> 00:40:27,780
l'm sorry, but we only have two guns,
or two rifles.

647
00:40:27,850 --> 00:40:30,341
-Right?
-l don't know. Don't start me to lying.

648
00:40:30,419 --> 00:40:32,910
-lsn't that right, John?
-l could check around.

649
00:40:32,988 --> 00:40:35,479
No, we couldn't possibly.
lt's a family tradition.

650
00:40:35,558 --> 00:40:38,459
Every year, just John and me.

651
00:40:39,128 --> 00:40:41,028
He could take my place.

652
00:40:41,597 --> 00:40:44,464
-Sure?
-Are you kidding? You're my guest.

653
00:40:44,533 --> 00:40:48,060
-What time do we start?
-Early.

654
00:40:49,305 --> 00:40:51,398
Very, very early.

655
00:40:51,473 --> 00:40:54,169
l don't wanna wake you up.
l'd better sleep in the den.

656
00:40:54,243 --> 00:40:57,838
-No, l don't think that's necessary.
-lt is necessary, my sweetest.

657
00:40:57,913 --> 00:40:59,380
-No.
-My darling.

658
00:40:59,448 --> 00:41:00,847
Good night.

659
00:41:09,058 --> 00:41:10,252
Oh, no.

660
00:41:33,249 --> 00:41:36,980
-Good morning. Ready for the hunt?
-The hunt.

661
00:41:37,419 --> 00:41:40,354
-Coffee?
-No, thank you. l don't want any coffee.

662
00:41:40,422 --> 00:41:43,687
-Did you sleep well last night?
-l slept okay. What is that?

663
00:41:43,759 --> 00:41:45,249
-What?
-That?

664
00:41:45,327 --> 00:41:47,192
-That's the sun.
-No.

665
00:41:47,263 --> 00:41:48,992
That's the sun? lt's all pink and blue.

666
00:41:49,064 --> 00:41:51,089
-You got any sugar?
-Sure.

667
00:41:53,702 --> 00:41:56,262
Sugar, someplace.

668
00:41:57,373 --> 00:42:00,604
-Sugar.
-Forget it. We ought to get going.

669
00:42:00,676 --> 00:42:02,837
-l have an orange. You want one?
-Let's go.

670
00:42:02,912 --> 00:42:04,641
-Two oranges?
-Yeah.

671
00:42:11,787 --> 00:42:14,779
Do you always wear all those clothes
when you go hunting?

672
00:42:14,857 --> 00:42:16,085
Always.

673
00:42:16,358 --> 00:42:19,521
-Do you ever get hot?
-Are you kidding me? Never.

674
00:43:22,725 --> 00:43:25,819
-You're staring at me.
-Sorry.

675
00:43:28,197 --> 00:43:30,893
lt's my hair, isn't it? lt's all poofy.

676
00:43:32,001 --> 00:43:33,662
No, you look fine.

677
00:43:33,902 --> 00:43:36,393
l was just wondering how you do it.

678
00:43:37,506 --> 00:43:40,907
-Do what?
-Live out here.

679
00:43:41,677 --> 00:43:44,475
Take care of a family. Maintain a career.

680
00:43:45,280 --> 00:43:46,907
Look like you do.

681
00:43:48,584 --> 00:43:52,645
-lt's gotta be the clean living.
-Or the facials l get every week.

682
00:43:53,322 --> 00:43:57,258
l know this might be hard for you
to accept, l actually like New York City.

683
00:43:57,326 --> 00:43:58,588
And the crime?

684
00:43:58,660 --> 00:44:00,059
-Theaters.
-Pollution.

685
00:44:00,129 --> 00:44:02,154
-Museums.
-Sex, drugs--

686
00:44:02,231 --> 00:44:04,859
Rock 'n' roll. l love the whole scene.

687
00:44:06,035 --> 00:44:08,970
Wouldn't seem so great
if you couldn't escape to Connecticut.

688
00:44:09,038 --> 00:44:10,528
Yeah, well.

689
00:44:11,940 --> 00:44:15,171
Hey, wait for me.
Would you carry my gun?

690
00:44:16,178 --> 00:44:17,167
And me?

691
00:44:21,483 --> 00:44:23,917
This is great. l really love this.

692
00:44:24,486 --> 00:44:26,420
Can we turn around now?

693
00:44:26,989 --> 00:44:30,356
You got everything, a beautiful home...

694
00:44:30,426 --> 00:44:33,520
successful career, terrific family.

695
00:44:33,595 --> 00:44:36,029
What more could you possibly want?

696
00:44:36,398 --> 00:44:39,094
Maybe to be appreciated
for more than my beautiful home...

697
00:44:39,168 --> 00:44:42,137
successful career, and incredible family.

698
00:44:43,338 --> 00:44:44,566
l know.

699
00:44:46,775 --> 00:44:47,969
You do?

700
00:44:49,278 --> 00:44:53,044
Yeah, you have grace, intelligence,
and a sense of humor.

701
00:44:57,453 --> 00:44:59,478
lt's a killer combination.

702
00:45:00,055 --> 00:45:04,890
Why, Jefferson Jones,
l actually think you're flirting with me.

703
00:45:10,232 --> 00:45:11,722
This is crazy.

704
00:45:24,780 --> 00:45:25,974
Listen.

705
00:45:29,051 --> 00:45:31,849
lt's a family. Aren't they sweet?

706
00:45:32,020 --> 00:45:34,420
What are you doing? You're not gonna....

707
00:45:43,465 --> 00:45:45,160
You didn't get it?

708
00:45:58,213 --> 00:46:00,010
Good morning, family!

709
00:46:04,553 --> 00:46:07,522
Forget it. Hey, l think they're coming.

710
00:46:10,659 --> 00:46:14,891
They're here! All right, everybody.
Let's make it look family time. Let's go.

711
00:46:14,963 --> 00:46:16,988
Elizabeth's here. Come on.

712
00:46:18,066 --> 00:46:21,627
lf you won't do it for me,
do it for Elizabeth.

713
00:46:22,171 --> 00:46:25,834
There you go. That's it. Perfect.

714
00:46:32,981 --> 00:46:37,577
''Captain Flash came screaming
from the sky from his rocket ship.''

715
00:46:37,653 --> 00:46:40,213
-Good morning!
-Good morning.

716
00:46:40,289 --> 00:46:41,756
Get a grip, Gramps.

717
00:46:41,823 --> 00:46:44,257
Yeah, Gramp, get a grip. Hi, Gorgeous.

718
00:46:44,326 --> 00:46:46,726
-Where's dinner?
-Buy a turkey.

719
00:46:46,795 --> 00:46:49,662
l missed a goose by a mile.
Something distracted me.

720
00:46:51,900 --> 00:46:53,299
lt sure did.

721
00:46:53,402 --> 00:46:56,633
You're just in time
to flip the flapjacks, dumpling.

722
00:46:56,705 --> 00:46:57,763
Flapjacks?

723
00:46:57,839 --> 00:47:00,637
l'm not in a flipping mood this morning.
Let Norah do it.

724
00:47:00,709 --> 00:47:02,700
-l don't flip. l scoop.
-You do?

725
00:47:02,778 --> 00:47:05,303
No, l want you
to flip me a flapjack, please.

726
00:47:05,380 --> 00:47:07,712
-You haven't done one in such a long time.
-What?

727
00:47:07,783 --> 00:47:10,547
For me. lf not for me,
do it for our honored guest, Jonesy.

728
00:47:10,619 --> 00:47:12,712
-Don't you wanna see her flapjack?
-Absolutely.

729
00:47:12,788 --> 00:47:16,280
-We'd love to see you flip a flapjack.
-You'd love to see me flip.

730
00:47:16,358 --> 00:47:18,451
-Flip a flapjack. For you?
-Yes.

731
00:47:18,527 --> 00:47:20,859
l'd be happy to, John. Happy to.

732
00:47:21,697 --> 00:47:23,631
-Oh, my God.
-This is gonna be good.

733
00:47:23,699 --> 00:47:25,462
-Norah, make way.
-Come on, Jonesy.

734
00:47:25,534 --> 00:47:28,526
All right, gather round, everyone.
This is it.

735
00:47:28,737 --> 00:47:30,102
This is it.

736
00:47:44,486 --> 00:47:47,387
-Yeah, all right!
-Do another one.

737
00:47:47,456 --> 00:47:50,254
No, sorry, folks, one is my limit.
Make way.

738
00:47:50,325 --> 00:47:52,384
l'll see you in a while.

739
00:47:55,364 --> 00:47:56,592
Go away.

740
00:48:02,170 --> 00:48:04,798
Oh, God. l know l'm gonna regret this.

741
00:48:05,474 --> 00:48:08,068
Okay, the door isn't locked. Come in.

742
00:48:11,913 --> 00:48:13,540
Liz, it's Tyler.

743
00:48:14,249 --> 00:48:15,910
-He's gone.
-What?

744
00:48:16,184 --> 00:48:19,278
l just checked the room.
He took all his things.

745
00:48:20,355 --> 00:48:22,949
Come on, sweetie. lt's all right.

746
00:48:25,894 --> 00:48:28,328
Come on, we'll think of something.

747
00:49:00,362 --> 00:49:01,886
Attention, all passengers.

748
00:49:01,963 --> 00:49:05,694
The train from Eastport leaving
to Hartford, Bristol and New Haven...

749
00:49:05,767 --> 00:49:07,701
has been delayed.

750
00:49:09,638 --> 00:49:13,199
Aren't you a little bit old
to be running away from home?

751
00:49:20,716 --> 00:49:23,446
Josie's really worried sick about you.

752
00:49:25,921 --> 00:49:29,721
l know this is going to surprise you,
but l know what you're going through.

753
00:49:29,791 --> 00:49:32,783
-l know just the way you feel.
-Good, then we needn't discuss it.

754
00:49:32,861 --> 00:49:34,954
You want that career so badly,
you can taste it.

755
00:49:35,030 --> 00:49:36,930
Nothing else can come in front of it.

756
00:49:36,998 --> 00:49:39,432
Let me ask you something:
lf you had to choose...

757
00:49:39,501 --> 00:49:42,527
if you had to give up Josie for your career,
would you do that?

758
00:49:42,604 --> 00:49:45,698
No, of course not. l would never want that.

759
00:49:45,774 --> 00:49:48,265
When you're starting out,
your career has to come first.

760
00:49:48,343 --> 00:49:51,835
Bull! lf you have someone to love
who loves you back...

761
00:49:51,913 --> 00:49:54,541
everything else is secondary.
l don't care what it is.

762
00:49:54,616 --> 00:49:56,914
Your home, your job,
your career, everything.

763
00:49:56,985 --> 00:49:58,680
Easy to say from where you sit.

764
00:49:58,754 --> 00:50:01,985
Especially from where l sit, mister.
Listen to me.

765
00:50:02,057 --> 00:50:04,958
All those wonderful things
that go with a sensational career...

766
00:50:05,026 --> 00:50:06,994
all those things don't mean diddlysquat...

767
00:50:07,062 --> 00:50:10,429
if you don't have someone special
to share them with.

768
00:50:10,665 --> 00:50:13,395
Do you understand
what l'm saying to you?

769
00:50:14,102 --> 00:50:15,296
Do you?

770
00:50:21,943 --> 00:50:24,741
Do you understand
what l'm saying to you?

771
00:50:25,147 --> 00:50:29,243
Tyler is a loser, with a capital ''L.''
He is a loser.

772
00:50:29,584 --> 00:50:33,748
And here's a beautiful woman like you
crying over a ding-dong loser.

773
00:50:33,922 --> 00:50:38,154
l can't believe it. l hate losers.
You know why? 'Cause l'm a winner.

774
00:50:38,326 --> 00:50:41,989
And you know what winners can do?
Winners know how to treat a woman.

775
00:50:42,297 --> 00:50:45,664
l know what a woman wants.
l know what a woman needs.

776
00:50:46,034 --> 00:50:48,059
l know what a woman feels.

777
00:50:50,272 --> 00:50:52,069
Take this Jefferson.

778
00:50:53,275 --> 00:50:55,869
You think he knows what a woman wants?
He's dumb.

779
00:50:55,944 --> 00:50:58,742
Lives in a log cabin,
dresses like Howdy Doody.

780
00:50:58,814 --> 00:51:00,145
What does he know about women?

781
00:51:00,215 --> 00:51:02,740
Do you think Elizabeth could go
for a guy like that?

782
00:51:02,818 --> 00:51:05,753
Think about it a little bit. A log cabin?

783
00:51:05,821 --> 00:51:08,381
She lives in this beautiful penthouse
in New York City...

784
00:51:08,457 --> 00:51:10,084
goes to the theater, parties with me.

785
00:51:10,158 --> 00:51:14,219
l mean, you got to be out of your head
to even consider something like that.

786
00:51:18,099 --> 00:51:19,760
What am l doing up here?

787
00:51:19,835 --> 00:51:21,462
Giving me advice.

788
00:51:22,471 --> 00:51:24,666
Oh, yeah, exactly. l got it.

789
00:51:25,974 --> 00:51:28,033
Go blonde and dump Tyler.

790
00:51:28,543 --> 00:51:30,670
Come on, give me a little smile.

791
00:51:39,387 --> 00:51:41,378
l've been looking for you.

792
00:51:42,090 --> 00:51:44,684
Hi. l had to run some errands.

793
00:51:45,760 --> 00:51:47,091
How you doing?

794
00:51:47,162 --> 00:51:50,529
Do you think John would mind
if l borrowed you for half an hour?

795
00:51:50,599 --> 00:51:52,658
Well, l'm not the family mule.

796
00:51:52,734 --> 00:51:55,294
You don't need his permission
to spend time with me.

797
00:51:55,370 --> 00:51:58,635
-lf you want to ask someone, ask me.
-You mean yes?

798
00:52:13,221 --> 00:52:14,950
l've been trying to think of a scene...

799
00:52:15,023 --> 00:52:17,651
where the husband and wife
kiss and make up.

800
00:52:17,726 --> 00:52:19,694
Maybe you can improvise.

801
00:52:21,563 --> 00:52:22,894
lmprovise?

802
00:52:25,400 --> 00:52:26,526
Okay.

803
00:52:28,737 --> 00:52:30,364
Josie, l'm sorry.

804
00:52:35,877 --> 00:52:38,107
l don't want to fight anymore.

805
00:52:42,751 --> 00:52:45,652
l'm bored. Can we do something?

806
00:52:47,856 --> 00:52:50,290
Kevin, l don't think this is a good time.

807
00:52:50,358 --> 00:52:51,950
Okay, l'll wait.

808
00:53:01,102 --> 00:53:04,560
-So you want to show me trees?
-A Christmas tree.

809
00:53:04,639 --> 00:53:07,574
-What do you mean?
-l saw it yesterday when l took a walk.

810
00:53:07,642 --> 00:53:11,476
l found this beautiful little tree.
lt reminded me of you.

811
00:53:12,614 --> 00:53:15,082
l've been thinking about it ever since.

812
00:53:15,150 --> 00:53:17,118
But we can't have our own tree.

813
00:53:17,185 --> 00:53:20,382
Listen, l know all about the show
and the set decorator.

814
00:53:20,455 --> 00:53:22,616
-You got to use your own decoration.
-Why?

815
00:53:22,691 --> 00:53:24,556
This is Christmas Eve.

816
00:53:24,960 --> 00:53:28,225
You got to have a tree for the kids.

817
00:53:29,130 --> 00:53:31,155
l think it's a great idea.

818
00:53:32,100 --> 00:53:34,967
-What do you think?
-This tree?

819
00:53:36,371 --> 00:53:38,339
lt's a nice little tree.

820
00:53:40,041 --> 00:53:41,565
Well, let's go.

821
00:54:19,214 --> 00:54:23,014
Look at you. Sitting there so innocent...

822
00:54:24,452 --> 00:54:25,919
so beautiful.

823
00:54:27,856 --> 00:54:30,552
You tried to make me think it was okay...

824
00:54:32,027 --> 00:54:33,494
but it isn't!

825
00:54:35,063 --> 00:54:36,587
You lied to me!

826
00:54:38,400 --> 00:54:39,662
You lied!

827
00:54:41,436 --> 00:54:43,927
And now it's time to pay the price.

828
00:54:47,175 --> 00:54:50,303
Okay, this is when you say:

829
00:54:51,479 --> 00:54:55,711
''Roger, you're sick. You need help.
Killing me won't solve anything.''

830
00:55:00,188 --> 00:55:02,053
Who writes this stuff?

831
00:55:03,758 --> 00:55:07,455
Certainly not you. You're too smart.

832
00:55:08,830 --> 00:55:11,492
You'll probably go
your whole adorable little life...

833
00:55:11,566 --> 00:55:14,228
never even watching a soap opera.

834
00:55:15,170 --> 00:55:17,229
You don't watch that stuff.

835
00:55:17,372 --> 00:55:19,863
Okay, back in character.

836
00:55:20,375 --> 00:55:24,141
You got to help me here, darling.
l got to think psychopath.

837
00:55:30,652 --> 00:55:32,244
Now's my chance.

838
00:55:32,754 --> 00:55:34,244
Finally alone!

839
00:55:36,057 --> 00:55:40,551
l've had about enough of you
crying all hours of the night!

840
00:55:41,563 --> 00:55:44,896
l got news for you. l'm going to sell you.

841
00:55:45,767 --> 00:55:49,828
That's right. We're broke,
so you're going to the highest bidder.

842
00:55:50,705 --> 00:55:54,766
A kid like you ought to keep us in gravy
for the rest of the year.

843
00:55:55,210 --> 00:55:58,145
And then l'll have to kill the rest of them !

844
00:55:59,481 --> 00:56:01,779
And l know just how l'll do it.

845
00:56:04,285 --> 00:56:06,219
But first things first.

846
00:56:09,224 --> 00:56:12,455
-Look, Josie.
-You look just like him.

847
00:56:13,294 --> 00:56:15,057
-Hey, they're back.
-Look.

848
00:56:15,130 --> 00:56:16,757
What's that?

849
00:56:16,865 --> 00:56:19,891
What does it look like?
lt's our Christmas tree.

850
00:56:19,968 --> 00:56:23,597
Where's the wooden stand
the lot guy always makes you pay $5 for?

851
00:56:23,671 --> 00:56:27,038
-lt didn't come from a lot.
-lt came from the forest.

852
00:56:27,809 --> 00:56:30,004
-Weird.
-l'll show you ''weird.''

853
00:56:47,796 --> 00:56:50,697
-Wipe your shoes off.
-Hey, tree time!

854
00:56:51,699 --> 00:56:54,793
-Don't get it all over.
-Careful, Kevin.

855
00:56:54,869 --> 00:56:56,894
Hi, Mommy. How was she?

856
00:56:56,971 --> 00:56:59,371
Right over there, in front of the window.

857
00:56:59,440 --> 00:57:02,136
-Where are the decorations?
-Decorations?

858
00:57:03,511 --> 00:57:04,739
Wait a minute.

859
00:57:04,813 --> 00:57:06,781
You got some, don't you?

860
00:57:07,615 --> 00:57:10,448
No. Actually, we had a burglary last year.

861
00:57:10,518 --> 00:57:12,645
They stole all of the decorations.

862
00:57:12,720 --> 00:57:15,553
What kind of a person
steals Christmas decorations?

863
00:57:15,623 --> 00:57:17,488
-A bad person.
-lt's very important.

864
00:57:17,559 --> 00:57:19,925
Just give me a second. Wait. What is it?

865
00:57:19,994 --> 00:57:22,189
-You got any popcorn?
-Yes.

866
00:57:22,263 --> 00:57:24,629
-Cranberries?
-We've everything you could want.

867
00:57:24,699 --> 00:57:27,668
-Yes, and l got our lights put out front.
-We're in business.

868
00:57:30,705 --> 00:57:34,664
All right, that's it. Come on.
No, don't pull on my cranberries.

869
00:57:35,910 --> 00:57:39,107
This is so frustrating
when you can't get these things undone.

870
00:57:39,714 --> 00:57:41,306
-What?
-Watch.

871
00:57:42,383 --> 00:57:45,580
Showoff. Look how easily he did that.

872
00:57:48,323 --> 00:57:52,054
-You guys, save some popcorn for me.
-Kevin, you guys finished down there?

873
00:57:52,160 --> 00:57:53,855
We're all finished.

874
00:57:58,233 --> 00:57:59,894
l have a surprise.

875
00:58:00,635 --> 00:58:03,866
-Look, l made cookies.
-Norah, you're so sweet.

876
00:58:04,072 --> 00:58:06,165
-Look at these.
-Aren't they beautiful?

877
00:58:06,241 --> 00:58:10,177
-Can we make some skull heads?
-Skull heads? That's a good idea.

878
00:58:10,245 --> 00:58:13,442
We'll all make skull heads.
All right, come on, Dad.

879
00:58:13,514 --> 00:58:16,574
-l am not making skull heads.
-Yes, you are now.

880
00:58:18,086 --> 00:58:19,849
What's a skull head?

881
00:58:20,622 --> 00:58:22,954
You got left with a cookie in your mouth.

882
00:58:23,024 --> 00:58:25,185
Look at that, they left us and stranded us.

883
00:58:25,260 --> 00:58:27,922
l guess we're gonna
have to decorate the tree?

884
00:58:27,996 --> 00:58:29,588
-l don't like that there.
-l guess so.

885
00:58:29,664 --> 00:58:31,359
Let me see where this belongs.

886
00:58:31,432 --> 00:58:33,992
-No, wait a minute.
-Right there.

887
00:58:34,068 --> 00:58:35,626
-You can't do that.
-Why not?

888
00:58:35,703 --> 00:58:38,570
lt's too big.
The big ones go on the bottom.

889
00:58:38,873 --> 00:58:41,740
l don't like it there.
Why do they have to go on the bottom?

890
00:58:41,809 --> 00:58:46,075
-Because the little ones go on top.
-l don't like rules. l hate rules.

891
00:58:49,817 --> 00:58:51,307
lt's perfect.

892
00:58:52,053 --> 00:58:55,045
You know, the top of the tree
looks really empty.

893
00:58:55,123 --> 00:58:59,219
l know just what to put up there.
l'll get it and come right back.

894
00:59:09,003 --> 00:59:12,962
-Something's wrong with Tyler.
-Tyler's all right. He's a little confused--

895
00:59:13,041 --> 00:59:14,941
There's something not right about him.

896
00:59:15,009 --> 00:59:17,569
There's something not right
about a lot of things here.

897
00:59:17,645 --> 00:59:20,978
-He could be dangerous.
-Come on, Alex.

898
00:59:21,049 --> 00:59:23,916
He's about as dangerous
as that little baby, Melissa.

899
00:59:23,985 --> 00:59:26,510
But, listen, he could ruin the show.

900
00:59:26,587 --> 00:59:28,953
lt's not too late to recast him.

901
00:59:29,457 --> 00:59:32,949
Alex, you really worry too much.
You really do.

902
00:59:33,027 --> 00:59:35,154
l mean, this is Christmas, munchkins.

903
00:59:35,229 --> 00:59:38,027
What in the world
could possibly go wrong?

904
00:59:44,038 --> 00:59:46,199
-What is that?
-lt's so beautiful.

905
00:59:46,274 --> 00:59:50,040
l'm telling you, l think a skull head
would look much better.

906
00:59:50,511 --> 00:59:52,809
-lt's perfect.
-Just like a pro.

907
00:59:56,084 --> 00:59:59,315
-l knew it would be just right.
-This is prettiful.

908
00:59:59,420 --> 01:00:01,251
-lt's nice.
-Let's light it.

909
01:00:01,322 --> 01:00:03,483
-Let's go for it.
-Go ahead, go for it.

910
01:00:03,558 --> 01:00:05,822
All right. Watch closely.

911
01:00:07,628 --> 01:00:08,925
All right!

912
01:00:11,299 --> 01:00:13,028
l can't believe it.

913
01:00:13,835 --> 01:00:15,234
We did that.

914
01:00:16,337 --> 01:00:19,568
-You act like you never had one before.
-l haven't!

915
01:00:19,707 --> 01:00:21,834
l mean, not this beautiful.

916
01:00:21,909 --> 01:00:26,573
l think this is the most beautiful tree
in the world. Never seen anything....

917
01:00:26,647 --> 01:00:29,707
l was gonna wait until morning,
but l just can't now.

918
01:00:29,784 --> 01:00:32,878
l'll explain when l get back.
Just wait a minute, okay?

919
01:00:33,755 --> 01:00:35,746
You're good at that, kid.

920
01:00:35,923 --> 01:00:37,550
-Jefferson.
-Gifts.

921
01:00:41,362 --> 01:00:42,954
Merry Christmas.

922
01:00:46,601 --> 01:00:48,899
-Sweetheart.
-l love gifts.

923
01:00:49,303 --> 01:00:51,100
This is so beautiful.

924
01:00:53,608 --> 01:00:56,133
l think l know what it is.

925
01:00:58,679 --> 01:01:00,670
Love Isn't Always Easy.

926
01:01:00,815 --> 01:01:02,976
This is exactly what we need.

927
01:01:03,051 --> 01:01:05,611
-lt's what you need.
-No, it's what you need.

928
01:01:06,054 --> 01:01:09,023
All right. This is just what l need.

929
01:01:20,034 --> 01:01:21,865
This is what we need.

930
01:01:23,571 --> 01:01:24,902
Thank you.

931
01:01:27,875 --> 01:01:29,206
Look at me.

932
01:01:33,781 --> 01:01:35,248
Where's Alex?

933
01:01:35,316 --> 01:01:37,045
Look what l got. l got a cone.

934
01:01:37,118 --> 01:01:40,144
l love these glasses. Thank you, Gramps.

935
01:01:42,924 --> 01:01:45,222
You know what?
We didn't get you anything.

936
01:01:45,293 --> 01:01:49,127
-l don't need anything. l've got you.
-Not so fast. l got something for you.

937
01:01:51,466 --> 01:01:54,958
-What is that?
-Since yours is up on the tree...

938
01:01:55,636 --> 01:01:57,627
l figured you might want that.

939
01:01:57,705 --> 01:02:00,003
-Look at me.
-How sweet.

940
01:02:00,074 --> 01:02:02,008
l love it. Thank you very much.

941
01:02:02,076 --> 01:02:03,907
Time to celebrate.

942
01:02:04,846 --> 01:02:06,336
Champagne!

943
01:02:10,718 --> 01:02:12,015
There.

944
01:02:12,120 --> 01:02:14,611
-Thank you. Here we go.
-Let me help.

945
01:02:15,790 --> 01:02:19,521
You can hold it, but don't drink.
l want to make a toast before you drink.

946
01:02:19,594 --> 01:02:21,585
Just a little toast here.

947
01:02:22,363 --> 01:02:23,853
To my family.

948
01:02:26,868 --> 01:02:29,564
-Oh, no.
-Who turned out the lights?

949
01:02:29,637 --> 01:02:32,629
lt's dark. Tyler, let's go make a baby
right now.

950
01:02:32,807 --> 01:02:35,435
Who's touching me? Get your hands off.

951
01:02:36,811 --> 01:02:40,542
'''Twas the night before Christmas,
when all through the house

952
01:02:40,915 --> 01:02:44,646
''Not a creature was stirring
not even a mouse

953
01:02:45,720 --> 01:02:49,019
''The stockings were hung
by the chimney with care

